"Gone with the Wind": Film legend Olivia de Havilland is dead
Film legend and Oscar winner Olivia de Havilland is dead.
Her spokeswoman for the German Press Agency confirmed that she died of natural causes in Paris on Sunday at the age of 104.
De Havilland was known for her role as Melanie Hamilton in the southern epic "Gone with the Wind" (1939).
Born in Tokyo to British parents, Olivia de Havilland moved to California as a toddler.
The Austrian theater man Max Reinhardt discovered the 19-year-old in the role of Hermia in Shakespeare's "Midsummer Night's Dream".
The film studio Warner Brothers signed her for seven years and made her big on the side of Eroll Flynn.
She made eight films with the heartbreaker.
In 1946 she won her first Oscar for the lead role of "To Each His Own".
The film ran in Germany under the title "Mutterherz".
Three years later came the award for best actress in William Wyler's "The Heiress".
She was also widely recognized as a neurotic eccentric in "The Dark Mirror" and "The Snake Pit".
Daphne du Maurier proposed her in 1952 for the lead role in the film adaptation of her novel "My Cousin Rachel".
The piece became a worldwide success.
She played in "Lullaby for a Corpse" with her long-time friend Bette Davis.
The son Benjamin emerged from his marriage to the writer Marcus Goodrich (1946 to 1953).
In Paris, de Havilland married the journalist Pierre Paul Galante and had the daughter Gisèle with him.
This marriage also broke up.
Rumors of an affair with former British Prime Minister Edward Heath have never been confirmed.
