Kalbitz expulsion from AfD confirmed - FDP speaks of "fig leaf"
The exclusion of Andreas Kalbitz from the AfD is, from the FDP's point of view, only a "fig leaf" and does not change the character of the party.
"The AfD is the parliamentary arm of the right-wing extremists in Germany.
Andreas Kalbitz is only part of the tip of the radical iceberg in the AfD, "said FDP domestic politician Benjamin Strasser of the dpa news agency in Berlin.
The Federal Arbitration Court of the AfD had confirmed the exclusion of Kalbitz on Saturday in Stuttgart after several hours of negotiations, which the federal board had decided by a majority in May.
Kalbitz is chairman of the AfD parliamentary group in the Brandenburg state parliament.
"If the AfD really wanted to consistently remove right-wing extremists from their party, functionaries like Björn Höcke and his supporters would have long since been excluded," said Strasser.
"But there is no political will in the AfD because right-wing extremism is now part of the party."
CSU General Secretary Markus Blume expressed himself in a similar way: "The fact that Andreas Kalbitz is now excluded says nothing and does not change anything," he told the "Welt am Sonntag".
"Rather, it speaks volumes how many frenetic supporters a right-wing extremist in the middle of the AfD still has."
Blume assumes that the AfD will end up below five percent again in future elections.
"The days of the AfD in parliaments are numbered".
Kalbitz was one of the spokesmen for the officially disbanded "wing" around the Thuringian AfD state and parliamentary group leader Björn Höcke; the Office for the Protection of the Constitution classifies the denigration as "secured right-wing extremist efforts".
In May, the AfD national board had thrown Kalbitz out of the party.
The reason he gave was that when he joined the party, Kalbitz had not given a previous membership in the now banned right-wing extremist "Heimattreuen Deutschen Jugend" (HDJ) and the Republicans.
Kalbitz denies membership in the HDJ.
The chairman of the left-wing parliamentary group in the Brandenburg state parliament, Sebastian Walter, also emphasized that the decision of the federal arbitration court did not change anything in the character of the AfD: "The wolf only ate chalk.
The AfD remains a right-wing extremist party, with or without Kalbitz ".
Neither the federal party nor the right wing will be weakened by this decision.
"The maneuver of the Meuthen troop is transparent.
They want to avoid further observation by the Office for the Protection of the Constitution and try to get through under the radar, "said Walter.
"The AfD is not getting rid of the ghosts it called.
An expulsion doesn't change anything, "commented the Brandenburg SPD General Secretary Erik Stohn on the decision in the Kalbitz case.
"Here the AfD regional association and the parliamentary group up to this day stuck to their right-wing leader".
The legal dispute over Kalbitz's membership in the AfD will continue.
This announced on Saturday that he would now proceed against the decision of the Federal Arbitration Court under civil law.
North Sea wind farms deliver a good 21 percent more electricity
The wind power plants on the German North Sea fed 11.51 terawatt hours of electricity into the grid in the first six months of the year.
That is a good 21 percent more than in the same period of the previous year, announced the network operator Tennet in Bayreuth.
Tennet is responsible for the transmission of the North Sea electricity to the mainland and the transmission through the German power grid.
The wind turbines on the Baltic Sea, which are not part of the Tennet grid area, have fed in a further 2.22 terawatt hours (TWh) of electricity.
Overall, wind power from the North Sea and Baltic Sea thus comes to 13.73 TWh, compared to a good 11.64 TWh in the first half of 2019.
The wind harvest at sea makes up almost 19 percent of the total wind power in Germany; that is about four percentage points more than a year ago.
New wind farms ensure higher generation capacities
The increased contribution of offshore wind energy results from the wind conditions and from higher generation capacities because new wind farms have been connected to the grid in the past twelve months.
If the 1270 wind power plants in the North Sea were all running at full power at the same time, they could theoretically generate 6.7 gigawatts of electricity.
The transmission capacity is sufficient for this; According to Tennet, it is 7.1 gigawatts.
It is expected to increase to 17 gigawatts in the German North Sea by 2030.
"In Germany and the Netherlands we will invest 20 billion euros in the expansion of the offshore grid connections", said Tennet managing director Tim Meyerjürgens.
In reality, wind farms cannot fully utilize their capacity at sea either, but reach around 40 percent.
The record day so far this year is January 2, when the North Sea wind farms generated more than six gigawatts of electricity.
On average, the North Sea wind turbines produce around 2.5 to 3.0 gigawatts of electricity, which corresponds to three to four nuclear power plants.
This could supply almost seven million households with electricity.
