After the meat industry, Heil wants to examine other industries
The Corona crisis brought the conditions in parts of the meat industry to light again.
Law tightening is imminent.
But are they legal - and will it stay that way?
Federal Labor Minister Hubertus Heil (SPD) wants to review other industries according to the strict regulations now planned against abuses in the meat industry.
"We will look at each branch and then take appropriate measures for the respective branch if necessary," said Heil to the German press agency in Berlin.
Germany's employers are already warning against generally restricting work contracts.
After the massive corona outbreak at the meat giant Tönnies in North Rhine-Westphalia, the federal cabinet wants to pass a law of salvation this Wednesday.
Large slaughterhouses should no longer be allowed to use external personnel for slaughtering, cutting and meat processing.
For this purpose, the use of contract workers and temporary workers is to be prohibited there.
Employer President Ingo Kramer told the dpa: "Stay away from a general restriction of work contracts and temporary employment, if you do not want to completely stall the economy".
Contracts for work and services are, for example, the basis for creating value for customers in large areas of the trades, the construction industry and plant engineering.
"The misconduct of individuals cannot destroy such an important instrument".
Heil assured: "My goal is not to ban contracts for work and services everywhere in the German economy".
Work contracts are useful.
"If an industrial company hires a craftsman to install a security system, it is a completely normal work contract".
The German meat industry considers a ban on work contracts and temporary work to be unconstitutional in its sector alone.
It cannot be explained why different labor laws should apply to portioning and packaging of cheese than to sausage, according to a statement on the proposed law, as reported by the "Neue Osnabrücker Zeitung" (Saturday).
In the event of a ban, the consumer price would rise by 10 to 20 percent per kilo and product.
According to the results of an audit by the NRW occupational health and safety administration, many Eastern European employees from contract companies worked 16 hours a day in the industry.
Often they did not have a break.
Wages were withheld for protective equipment or rent.
It was also found that the housing situation for employees was often miserable.
Heil said that a relatively strict law came into force for the meat industry as early as 2017.
However, these were bypassed by "tricky constructions".
"Now we have to clean up fundamentally".
The politician announced: "In the labor protection law, which we want to pass in the cabinet at the end of July, there are also measures that not only affect the meat industry - for example higher inspection rates for occupational health and safety or clear criteria for shared accommodation".
The draft presented to the dpa includes changes to the law on safeguarding workers' rights in the meat industry and the law on occupational health and safety.
Brandenburg's consumer protection minister Ursula Nonnemacher (Greens) considers more intensive controls to be necessary.
"I would like to see that we can do even more controls in many areas of supervision: food controls, animal welfare, all sorts of things, including animal transport," said Nonnemacher on Sunday in the RBB program "Brandenburg aktuell".
But more staff positions are needed for more controls.
