Baden-Württemberg: Over 250 illegal car races recorded
Stuttgart - Despite all the threatened fines and court rulings, drivers continue to give gas in countless illegal races on the streets of Baden-Württemberg: In the past year and the first four months of this year, the police in the southwest have already registered more than 250 illegal car races.
There are no comparative values for the years before, but the speeders are making the judicial authorities more and more work: A total of 155 investigations into illegal races were conducted in the public prosecutor's offices between Konstanz and Mannheim in 2018, one year later there were already 252 and this year up to At the beginning of June already 151.
The races were less about organized events, as can be seen from the answer from the Interior Ministry to a request from the SPD in the state parliament.
In most cases, the drivers spontaneously competed against each other or they fled from the police - this is also reported as an illegal race.
Mainly German men between the ages of 18 and 60 sat at the wheel.
113 fines - 15 imprisonment
Only in comparatively few cases are the speeders caught and asked to pay: According to the Ministry of the Interior, a total of 113 fines and 15 prison sentences have been imposed since 2018.
But there is no evidence that the number of illegal car races is actually increasing.
Rather, other drivers reacted more sensitively than before because of the number of tragic accidents and processes in the past and reported more often, said a ministry spokesman.
The Autobahn 8 is particularly popular with racers. Drivers there slow down the traffic again and again in order to make room and use the free track for a race.
Last August, a dozen drivers were caught near Kirchheim unter Teck, three months earlier there were even 18 drivers on the A8 near Merklingen.
A81 is the most popular "racetrack"
The police even register more races on the A81 than on any other federal motorway.
With a speed limit, attempts are made there to slow down the speeders on the particularly affected section between Engen and Geisingen.
The mostly high-priced and souped-up sports and luxury cars often have Swiss license plates, because the drivers move to Germany because of the high penalties for driving too fast and car racing in the neighboring country.
For the SPD, the speed limit must not be reduced to a few routes: "With a general speed limit of 130 kilometers per hour, we would get rid of this problem on motorways," says Martin Rivoir, the traffic expert for the SPD parliamentary group.
"The inhibition threshold for speeders would be significantly higher if you weren't allowed to legally travel at 200 kilometers per hour and more here and there."
Rivoir thinks less of education or image campaigns: "Anyone who disregards all the rules in such a way and not only jeopardizes their own lives but also the lives of other road users can hardly be reached with common sense."
ADAC calls for stronger action from the police
For the ADAC, however, this is not enough: "We are assuming that the speed limits will not scare them off," says Holger Bach, Head of the Traffic and Environment Department at ADAC Württemberg.
He calls for additional and tougher controls on the affected routes.
The high-speed test of strength often turns into painful and serious seriousness: Since January 2019 and until April 2020, three people have died in the races across the country, two bystanders in a nightly crash in downtown Stuttgart and one in Gerlingen.
Two young men are said to have delivered a car race there in November.
One of the vehicles came off the road, hit a garden wall and lay on its side, the 18-year-old passenger died.
21 other people were injured in races over the past two years.
In the opinion of Interior Minister Thomas Strobl, however, stricter penalties are not necessary.
