Green was born in 1946 to a Jewish working class family in Bethnal Green, London.
From a young age he was enthusiastic about US blues musicians such as BB King and Muddy Waters.
At the age of eleven he learned the first guitar fingerings.
The teenager began playing the guitar professionally at the age of 15 and five years later got the chance to take the stage as lead guitarist for the instrumental band Peter B's Looners.
A little later he was hired to replace his idol Eric Clapton with the Bluesbreakers.
In the midst of the blues boom, Green founded Fleetwood Mac in the summer of 1967 together with his Bluesbreakers colleagues Mick Fleetwood and John McVie.
The song "Albatross" composed by Green gave the group their first number 1 hit in the winter of 1968/69 and catapulted them to the top of the British music scene.
But the rapid rise soon showed its downsides: Green couldn't cope with the media hype, his experiments with the drug LSD became more and more extreme.
He later commented on life between music and addiction in an interview: "The worst thing that has happened to me in life is the drugs - the best was to land a number 1 hit".
Towards the end of the decade, Green surprisingly achieved a respectable success in 1979 with an album inspired by religious themes.
Fleetwood Mac swam meanwhile without him in a new formation on a wave of success.
Her album "Rumors", released in 1977, sold more than 40 million copies worldwide.
Despite various small solo successes, Green did not make a major comeback until he started again in 1996 with a group of musician friends.
The British Daily Telegraph spoke of a rock star who had returned to earth.
Free of drugs, Green released a few albums with the Peter Green Splinter Group until the band split up in 2004.
For music experts he was already a blues legend during his lifetime - and with his smooth sound one of the most influential guitarists of the past decades.
